Abuja – The Minister of Science and Technology, Dr. Ogbonnaya Onu yesterday disclosed that the Federal Government would save at least N3.6trn in the next five years through the Natural Strategy for Competitiveness in Raw Materials (NSCRM). The minister also said that the government was set to develop necessary technology to promote innovation and make research by its agencies to be industry–driven. Onu stated this in Abuja when Engr. Mansur Ahmed, President of the Manufacturers Association of Nigeria (MAN) paid him a courtesy visit in his office. According to him, henceforth, research efforts by the Federal Ministry of Science and Technology would be industry-driven and targets national needs, adding that it would enable Nigeria to stop the importation of what it could produce locally. Onu further emphasised that his ministry had developed a leather policy that was expected to boost the leather industry and spearhead industrialisation in the country. The minister also said that the biotechnology cotton variety recently developed and launched by National Biotechnology Development Agency (NABDA) would go a long way in resuscitating Nigeria’s moribund textile industry and rejuvenate the cotton Sector. Earlier, Ahmed, President, MAN had sought Federal Government’s partnership in the improvement of local raw materials and value addition to boost industralisation in the country. He explained that such partnership between the public and private sector would help to develop various sub-sectors of the economy, which would in turn create jobs and significantly reduce the importation of goods into the country. He used the opportunity to invite the minister to MAN’s forthcoming three-day expo with the theme: ‘Optimising the Value-chain in the Manufacturing Sector to Achieve Growth,’ adding that MAN would create the platform   for mutual engagements of all stakeholders in the manufacturing sector during the expo.